Introduction

This project investigates how physiological and lifestyle factors relate to blood pressure. The dataset is simulated for practice purposes and includes variables such as age, weight, body surface area, pulse, stress, and duration of elevated blood pressure. All analysis was performed using R Studio.

Key Takeaways: Exploration and visualization help detect patterns in the data. Simulated datasets are useful for testing regression models.

The dataset contains 20 individuals, each representing one observation in a physiological or medical test. Every column describes a measurement related to the persons body or their response during the test.

Variables:

Blood pressure (BP, in mm Hg) age (Age, in years <- factors) weight (Weight, in kg) body surface area (BSA, in sq m) duration of hypertension (DUR, in years) basal pulse (Pulse, in beats per minute <- factors) Stress index (Stress <-factors)

# Simple linear regression model - one predictor

Across the six simple linear models, Weight stands out as the strongest predictor of blood pressure. The BPWeight model explains about 90 percent of the variation in blood pressure and shows a very strong, highly significant positive relationship.

BSA also performs well, with a solid positive effect and an R around 0.75. Pulse and Age show moderate positive relationships with BP, both statistically significant but explaining less variation.

In contrast, Duration and Stress show no meaningful relationship with blood pressure. Their slopes are small, not significant, and the R values are near zero.

Overall, the results suggest that body size variables, especially Weight, are the most useful single predictors of blood pressure in this dataset.

#Is the model statistically significant?

I analyzed six simple linear regression models to see how different variables predict blood pressure. Weight is by far the strongest predictor. Its model explains about 90 percent of the variation in BP and shows a very strong positive effect. BSA also has a strong positive relationship with BP, with an R around 0.75. Age and Pulse show moderate positive effects, both significant but weaker.

In contrast, Duration and Stress do not meaningfully predict BP. Their slopes are small, not significant, and their R values are close to zero.

Overall, body size measures, especially Weight, provide the best single-variable explanation of blood pressure in this dataset.

Multiple linear regression- with all the predictors

In the full regression model, almost all variation in blood pressure is explained (R 0.996). Weight and Age remain the strongest predictors, with BSA also contributing. The other variables (Duration, Pulse, Stress) become weak and non-significant once body-size measures are included. Overall, blood pressure in this dataset is mainly linked to body size.

Variance inflation factors

The full model explains almost all variation in blood pressure (R 0.996). Age, Weight, and BSA are the strongest predictors, all highly significant. Their correlations are also high, and the VIF values show that Weight and BSA have substantial collinearity (VIF > 5), which weakens the models stability.

Compare models

BP is mainly explained by Age, Weight, and BSA. These three predictors together give an almost perfect model (R 0.996). Weight alone is very strong (R 0.90), BSA and Age also strong. Other variables (Dur, Pulse, Stress) add little once body size is included.

High correlations and high VIFs show strong collinearity between Weight and BSA.

A reduced model BP ~ Age + BSA + Dur + Pulse + Stress still shows BSA and Pulse matter most, but performs worse than including Weight.

Best model: Age + Weight + BSA.

mdlSIMP <- lm(BP ~ Weight, data=bloodData)       #b

Check for outliars

n=20
p=7
cr_value = qt(0.05/(2*n),n-p-1, lower.tail = F)
cr_value

srTOT = rstudent(mdlBIC)
which(abs(srTOT)>cr_value)
